00:35:15.810 --> 00:35:20.120
So if I were to go
exactly down here,

00:35:20.120 --> 00:35:25.630
you see what I would
get is a curve that

00:35:25.630 --> 00:35:31.780
is kind of like this-- comes
and hogs the vertical axis

00:35:31.780 --> 00:35:36.650
and then does that,
which is in the sense

00:35:36.650 --> 00:35:41.100
that we were discussing
before identical to the curve

00:35:41.100 --> 00:35:47.530
that you have for the isoterm
of the liquid gas coexistence.

00:35:47.530 --> 00:35:48.740
What do I mean?

00:35:48.740 --> 00:35:53.040
I could do the same
type of collapse of data

00:35:53.040 --> 00:35:54.710
that I showed you
before that I was

00:35:54.710 --> 00:35:57.030
doing for the coexistence curve.

00:35:57.030 --> 00:36:01.570
I can do that for these
inverted coexistence curves.

00:36:01.570 --> 00:36:05.900
I can do the same collapse
for this critical isoterm

00:36:05.900 --> 00:36:07.660
of the ferromagnet.

00:36:07.660 --> 00:36:11.490
And it would fall on top
of the critical isoterm

00:36:11.490 --> 00:36:16.700
that I would have for neon,
argon, krypton, anything else.

00:36:16.700 --> 00:36:19.970
So that is that kind of
overall universality.

00:36:23.670 --> 00:36:28.098
Now-- yes?

00:36:28.098 --> 00:36:30.222
AUDIENCE: In this
[INAUDIBLE], why didn't you

00:36:30.222 --> 00:36:33.300
draw the full loop
of hysteresis?

00:36:33.300 --> 00:36:35.780
PROFESSOR: Because I'm
interested at this point

00:36:35.780 --> 00:36:37.990
with equilibrium phenomena.

00:36:37.990 --> 00:36:41.050
Hysteresis is a non
equilibrium thing.

00:36:41.050 --> 00:36:45.670
So depending on how rapid you
cool things or not cool things,

00:36:45.670 --> 00:36:49.070
you will get larger curves--
larger hysteresis curves.

00:36:49.070 --> 00:36:51.236
AUDIENCE: So what
would it have been

00:36:51.236 --> 00:36:54.364
if we had high-- wasn't
[INAUDIBLE] fields

00:36:54.364 --> 00:36:58.220
that were slowly reduce it to 0?

00:36:58.220 --> 00:37:00.450
And then go a little
bit beyond and then

00:37:00.450 --> 00:37:04.050
just stay in that
state for a long time?

00:37:04.050 --> 00:37:04.650
Will the--

00:37:04.650 --> 00:37:05.274
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:37:05.274 --> 00:37:08.636
If you wait sufficiently
long time, which

00:37:08.636 --> 00:37:10.010
is the definition
of equilibrium,

00:37:10.010 --> 00:37:13.450
you would follow the
curve that I have drawn.

00:37:13.450 --> 00:37:16.060
There would be-- so the
size of the hysteresis loop

00:37:16.060 --> 00:37:21.180
will go down as the amount
of time that you wait.

00:37:21.180 --> 00:37:23.080
Except that in
order to see this,

00:37:23.080 --> 00:37:25.789
you may have to wait longer
than the age of the universe.

00:37:25.789 --> 00:37:26.330
I don't know.

00:37:26.330 --> 00:37:30.644
But in principle, that's
what's going to happen.

00:37:30.644 --> 00:37:33.380
AUDIENCE: I have
a question here.

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:37.040
PROFESSOR: Yes

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:41.200
AUDIENCE: When you create
the flat line for temperature

00:37:41.200 --> 00:37:42.627
below the critical one--

00:37:42.627 --> 00:37:43.210
PROFESSOR: Yes

00:37:43.210 --> 00:37:45.390
AUDIENCE: --are you
essentially doing

00:37:45.390 --> 00:37:47.180
sort of a Maxwell
construction again?

00:37:47.180 --> 00:37:51.840
Or is that too
much even for this?

00:37:51.840 --> 00:37:52.480
PROFESSOR: No.

00:37:52.480 --> 00:37:54.720
I mean, I haven't done
any theoretical work.

00:37:54.720 --> 00:37:57.920
At this point, I'm just
giving you observation.

00:37:57.920 --> 00:38:00.420
Once we start to
give theory, there

00:38:00.420 --> 00:38:03.370
is a type of theory
for the magnet that

00:38:03.370 --> 00:38:06.140
is the analog of
Maxwell's construction

00:38:06.140 --> 00:38:10.210
that you would do for the
case of the liquid gas.

00:38:10.210 --> 00:38:14.730
Indeed, you will have that
as the first problem set.

00:38:14.730 --> 00:38:16.435
So you can figure
it out for yourself.

00:38:19.000 --> 00:38:22.430
Anything else?

00:38:22.430 --> 00:38:23.980
OK.

00:38:23.980 --> 00:38:29.830
So I kind of emphasized
that functional forms

00:38:29.830 --> 00:38:32.720
are the things
that are universal.

00:38:32.720 --> 00:38:35.465
And so in the context
of the magnet,

00:38:35.465 --> 00:38:40.970
it is more clear
how to characterize

00:38:40.970 --> 00:38:43.090
these functional forms.

00:38:43.090 --> 00:38:47.010
So one of the things
that we have over here

00:38:47.010 --> 00:38:52.850
is that if I plot the true
equilibrium magnetization

00:38:52.850 --> 00:38:57.230
as a function of temperature
for fields that are 0--

00:38:57.230 --> 00:38:58.660
so H equals to 0.

00:38:58.660 --> 00:39:03.450
If I start along
the 0 field line,

00:39:03.450 --> 00:39:09.230
then all the way up
to TC, magnetization

00:39:09.230 --> 00:39:12.180
at high temperatures
is of course 0.

00:39:12.180 --> 00:39:13.830
You're dealing
with a paramagnet.

00:39:13.830 --> 00:39:16.090
By definition, it
has no magnetization.

00:39:16.090 --> 00:39:18.950
When you go below
TC, you'll have

00:39:18.950 --> 00:39:22.210
a system that is
spontaneously magnetized.

00:39:22.210 --> 00:39:25.500
Again, exactly
what that means is

00:39:25.500 --> 00:39:28.260
it needs a little
bit of clarification.

00:39:28.260 --> 00:39:31.810
Because it does depend on
the direction of your field.

00:39:31.810 --> 00:39:35.150
The magnitude of
it is well defined.

00:39:35.150 --> 00:39:38.230
If I go from H to
minus H, the sine of it

00:39:38.230 --> 00:39:39.870
could potentially change.

00:39:39.870 --> 00:39:43.786
But the magnitude has
a form such as this.

00:39:43.786 --> 00:39:48.030
It is again very
similar, if you like,

00:39:48.030 --> 00:39:51.020
to half of that
co existence curve

00:39:51.020 --> 00:39:53.560
that we had for the liquid gas.

00:39:53.560 --> 00:40:00.180
And we look at the behavior
that you have in this vicinity.

00:40:00.180 --> 00:40:04.630
And we find that is
well-described by a power law.

00:40:04.630 --> 00:40:13.880
So we say that M as T goes
to TC for H equals to 0

00:40:13.880 --> 00:40:20.630
is characterized or is
proportional to TC minus T

00:40:20.630 --> 00:40:25.345
to an exponent that is
given the symbol beta.

00:40:29.370 --> 00:40:32.880
Now, sometimes you can't
write this as TC minus T

00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:35.220
to the-- make it dimension.

00:40:35.220 --> 00:40:36.070
It doesn't matter.

00:40:36.070 --> 00:40:37.730
It's the same exponent.

00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:40.950
Sometimes in order not to have
to write all of this thing

00:40:40.950 --> 00:40:44.440
again and again, you
call this small T.

00:40:44.440 --> 00:40:48.160
It's just that
reduced temperature

00:40:48.160 --> 00:40:50.620
from the critical point.

00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:55.440
And so basically, what we
have is that T to the beta

00:40:55.440 --> 00:40:59.860
characterizes the singularity
of the coexistence line,

00:40:59.860 --> 00:41:04.030
the magnetization [INAUDIBLE].

00:41:04.030 --> 00:41:11.750
Now, rather then sitting
at H equals to 0,

00:41:11.750 --> 00:41:16.060
I could have sat exactly
at T equals to TC

00:41:16.060 --> 00:41:22.310
and merely H. So essentially,
this is the curve.

00:41:22.310 --> 00:41:23.850
I say that T equals to TC.

00:41:23.850 --> 00:41:26.340
This is the blue curve.

00:41:26.340 --> 00:41:31.300
We see that new blue has this
characteristic form that it

00:41:31.300 --> 00:41:35.380
also comes to 0 not linearly.

00:41:35.380 --> 00:41:39.902
So there is an exponent
that characterizes that.

00:41:39.902 --> 00:41:45.200
that again is typically
written as 1 over delta.

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:50.260
So you can see that if I go
back to the critical isoterm

00:41:50.260 --> 00:41:52.760
of the liquid gas system.

00:41:52.760 --> 00:41:57.080
For the liquid gas system,
I would conclude that, say,

00:41:57.080 --> 00:42:02.630
delta v goes like delta P
to the power of delta or one

00:42:02.630 --> 00:42:04.870
goes with the other to
the power of 1 if it.

00:42:04.870 --> 00:42:10.680
So essentially, the
shapes of these two things

00:42:10.680 --> 00:42:12.757
are very much
related, characterized

00:42:12.757 --> 00:42:13.715
by these two exponents.

00:42:18.470 --> 00:42:19.405
What else?

00:42:23.890 --> 00:42:28.159
Another thing that we can
certainly measure for a magnet

00:42:28.159 --> 00:42:29.075
is the susceptibility.

00:42:36.020 --> 00:42:41.130
So chi-- let's measure it
as a function of temperature

00:42:41.130 --> 00:42:44.960
but for field equal to 0.

00:42:44.960 --> 00:42:51.370
So basically, I sit eventually
at the equals to TC.

00:42:51.370 --> 00:42:53.660
But I put on a
small magnetic field

00:42:53.660 --> 00:42:56.970
and see how the
magnetization changes.

00:42:56.970 --> 00:43:00.310
You can see that as
long as I am above TC

00:43:00.310 --> 00:43:05.430
in the paramagnetic phase, there
is a linear relationship here.

00:43:05.430 --> 00:43:11.060
Chi is proportional to H.
But the proportionality here

00:43:11.060 --> 00:43:12.990
is the susceptibility.

00:43:12.990 --> 00:43:17.820
As I get closer to C, that
susceptibility diverges.

00:43:17.820 --> 00:43:23.820
OK, so chi is
proportional to T diverges

00:43:23.820 --> 00:43:27.230
with an exponent that
is indicated by gamma.

00:43:27.230 --> 00:43:30.180
Actually, let me be a
little bit more precise.

00:43:30.180 --> 00:43:35.980
So what I have said is that
if I plot the susceptibility

00:43:35.980 --> 00:43:41.800
as a function of temperature
at TC, it diverges.

00:43:45.230 --> 00:43:50.550
I could also calculate something
similar to that below TC.

00:43:50.550 --> 00:43:52.290
Below TC, it is
true that I already

00:43:52.290 --> 00:43:54.626
have some magnetization.

00:43:54.626 --> 00:43:57.480
But if I put on
a magnetic field,

00:43:57.480 --> 00:44:00.580
the magnetization will go up.

00:44:00.580 --> 00:44:03.510
And I can define
the slope of that

00:44:03.510 --> 00:44:07.920
as being the
susceptibility below TC.

00:44:07.920 --> 00:44:11.302
And again, as I
approach TC from below,

00:44:11.302 --> 00:44:14.600
that susceptibility
also diverges.

00:44:14.600 --> 00:44:19.520
So there is a susceptibility
that comes like this.

00:44:19.520 --> 00:44:21.770
So you would say, OK.

00:44:21.770 --> 00:44:24.870
There's a susceptibility above.

00:44:24.870 --> 00:44:27.340
And there is a
susceptibility below.

00:44:27.340 --> 00:44:30.975
And maybe they diverge
with different exponents.

00:44:30.975 --> 00:44:34.100
at this point, we don't know.

00:44:34.100 --> 00:44:35.620
Yes or no.

00:44:35.620 --> 00:44:40.970
We will show shortly that
indeed the two gammas are really

00:44:40.970 --> 00:44:45.476
the same and using one exponent
is sufficient for that story.

00:44:49.050 --> 00:44:53.650
And analog of susceptibility
in the case of the liquid gas

00:44:53.650 --> 00:44:55.860
would be the compressibility.

00:44:55.860 --> 00:44:58.740
And the compressibility
is related somehow

00:44:58.740 --> 00:45:03.260
to the inverse of
these PV curve slopes.

00:45:03.260 --> 00:45:07.590
We know that the sign of it has
to be negative for stability.

00:45:07.590 --> 00:45:09.980
But right on the
critical isoterm,

00:45:09.980 --> 00:45:14.180
you see that this slope goes
to 0 or its inverse diverges.

00:45:14.180 --> 00:45:19.550
So there is, again, the same
exponent gamma for some magnets

00:45:19.550 --> 00:45:20.897
also describes that divergence.

00:45:24.560 --> 00:45:28.340
Susceptibility is an example
of a response function.

00:45:28.340 --> 00:45:31.360
You perturb the system
and see how it responds.

00:45:31.360 --> 00:45:33.250
Another response
function that we've

00:45:33.250 --> 00:45:39.780
seen is the heat capacity where
you put heat into this system

00:45:39.780 --> 00:45:41.560
or you try to change
the temperature

00:45:41.560 --> 00:45:44.350
and see how the heat
energy is modified.

00:45:47.330 --> 00:45:53.400
And again, we
experimentally observe.

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:55.590
We already saw
something like this

00:45:55.590 --> 00:45:57.470
when we were discussing
the super fluid

00:45:57.470 --> 00:46:00.640
transition, the lambda
transition-- that the heat

00:46:00.640 --> 00:46:06.700
capacity as a function of
temperature at some transition

00:46:06.700 --> 00:46:09.785
temperatures happens to diverge.

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:16.450
And in principle,
one can again look

00:46:16.450 --> 00:46:19.250
at the two sides
of the transition

00:46:19.250 --> 00:46:24.460
and characterize them by
divergences that are typically

00:46:24.460 --> 00:46:27.300
indicated by the exponent alpha.

00:46:27.300 --> 00:46:30.990
Again, you will see
that there are reasons

00:46:30.990 --> 00:46:34.980
why there is only one
exponent [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:34.980 --> 00:46:39.310
So this is essentially
the only part

00:46:39.310 --> 00:46:42.640
where there is some
zoology involved.

00:46:42.640 --> 00:46:45.330
You have to remember
and learn where

00:46:45.330 --> 00:46:47.990
the different
exponents come from.

00:46:47.990 --> 00:46:51.390
The rest of it, I hope, is
very logical-- but which

00:46:51.390 --> 00:46:54.139
one is alpha, which one's
beta, which one's gamma.

00:46:54.139 --> 00:46:56.472
There's four things, five
things you should [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:59.310 --> 00:47:01.900
OK?

00:47:01.900 --> 00:47:06.320
Now, the next thing
that I want to do

00:47:06.320 --> 00:47:11.000
is to show you that the
two things that we looked

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:13.480
at about the liquid
gas transition--

00:47:13.480 --> 00:47:16.870
in fact, one of them
implies the other.

00:47:16.870 --> 00:47:20.440
So we said that
essentially by continuity,

00:47:20.440 --> 00:47:24.040
when I look at the shape
of this critical isoterm,

00:47:24.040 --> 00:47:27.260
it come down in this zero slope.

00:47:27.260 --> 00:47:30.530
When, again, to continuously
join the type of curve

00:47:30.530 --> 00:47:33.465
that I have for T greater
than TC of magnetization

00:47:33.465 --> 00:47:36.230
and T less than
TC below, I should

00:47:36.230 --> 00:47:39.750
have a curve that
comes and hogs the axis

00:47:39.750 --> 00:47:41.510
or has infinite susceptibility.

00:47:44.300 --> 00:47:48.220
I will show you that the
infinite susceptibility does,

00:47:48.220 --> 00:47:52.510
in fact imply, that you must
have collective behavior.

00:47:52.510 --> 00:47:56.130
That this critical
opalescence that we saw

00:47:56.130 --> 00:47:59.870
is inseparable from
the fact that you

00:47:59.870 --> 00:48:03.130
have diverging susceptibility.

00:48:03.130 --> 00:48:04.940
I'll show that in the
case of the magnet.

00:48:04.940 --> 00:48:09.110
But it also applies, of course,
to the critical opalescence.

00:48:09.110 --> 00:48:12.290
So let's do a little
bit of thermodynamics.

00:48:12.290 --> 00:48:18.770
So I can imagine if I have
some kind of Hamiltonia that

00:48:18.770 --> 00:48:23.810
describes my interactions
among the spins in my argon

00:48:23.810 --> 00:48:26.540
or any other magnet that I have.

00:48:26.540 --> 00:48:31.060
And if I was to calculate
a partition function, what

00:48:31.060 --> 00:48:34.170
I need to do would
be to trace over

00:48:34.170 --> 00:48:38.310
all degrees of freedom
of this system.

00:48:38.310 --> 00:48:41.600
Now, for the case of the
magnet, it is more convenient

00:48:41.600 --> 00:48:46.030
actually to look at the ensemble
that is corresponding to this.

00:48:46.030 --> 00:48:49.810
That is, fix the magnetic field
and allow the magnetization

00:48:49.810 --> 00:48:51.960
to decide where it wants to be.

00:48:51.960 --> 00:48:54.110
So I really want
to evaluate things

00:48:54.110 --> 00:48:58.560
in this ensemble, which
really to be precise,

00:48:58.560 --> 00:49:03.280
is not the [INAUDIBLE] ensemble,
but the Gibbs ensemble.

00:49:03.280 --> 00:49:05.180
So this should be a
Gibbs free energy.

00:49:05.180 --> 00:49:07.290
This should be a Gibbs
partition function.

00:49:07.290 --> 00:49:11.100
But traditionally, most
texts including my notes

00:49:11.100 --> 00:49:13.750
ignore that difference
and log of this.

00:49:13.750 --> 00:49:16.380
Rather than calling
it G, we will call F.

00:49:16.380 --> 00:49:20.600
But that doesn't
make much difference.

00:49:20.600 --> 00:49:25.760
This clearly is a function
of temperature and H.

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:32.040
Now, if I wanted-- let's
imagine that always we

00:49:32.040 --> 00:49:33.810
put the magnetic field
in one direction.

00:49:33.810 --> 00:49:35.932
So I don't have to
worry for the time being

00:49:35.932 --> 00:49:37.510
about vectorial aspect.

00:49:37.510 --> 00:49:40.670
When you go back to
the vectorial aspect

00:49:40.670 --> 00:49:44.050
later on, clearly--
actually this

00:49:44.050 --> 00:49:48.420
is the net magnetization
of the system.

00:49:48.420 --> 00:49:50.045
If I have a piece
of iron, it would

00:49:50.045 --> 00:49:53.770
be the magnetization
of the entire iron.

00:49:53.770 --> 00:49:57.190
And the average of
that magnetization,

00:49:57.190 --> 00:50:00.040
given temperature
and field, et cetera,

00:50:00.040 --> 00:50:07.890
I can obtain by taking
the log z by D beta H.

00:50:07.890 --> 00:50:11.830
Because when I do that, I
go back inside the trace,

00:50:11.830 --> 00:50:13.890
take a derivative in
respect to beta H.

00:50:13.890 --> 00:50:23.410
And I have a trace of M into
the minus beta H plus beta HM,

00:50:23.410 --> 00:50:29.720
which is how the different
probabilities are rated once

00:50:29.720 --> 00:50:32.520
because of the log z.

00:50:32.520 --> 00:50:34.620
In a derivative,
I have a 1 over z

00:50:34.620 --> 00:50:38.730
to make this more properly
normalized probabilities.

00:50:38.730 --> 00:50:40.510
So that's the standard story.

00:50:43.780 --> 00:50:49.740
Now if I were to take
another derivative,

00:50:49.740 --> 00:50:54.160
if I were to take
a derivative of M

00:50:54.160 --> 00:50:59.320
with respect to H, which is
what the susceptibility is,

00:50:59.320 --> 00:51:00.770
after all.

00:51:00.770 --> 00:51:02.790
So the sensitivity
of the system--

00:51:02.790 --> 00:51:04.660
there is the derivative
of magnetization

00:51:04.660 --> 00:51:07.240
with respect to H.

00:51:07.240 --> 00:51:11.270
It is the same thing
as beta derivative

00:51:11.270 --> 00:51:16.540
of M with respect to
beta H, of course.

00:51:16.540 --> 00:51:19.690
So I have to go to this
expression that I have on top

00:51:19.690 --> 00:51:23.260
and take another derivative
with respect to beta H.

00:51:23.260 --> 00:51:29.220
The derivative can act on beta
H that is in the numerator.

00:51:29.220 --> 00:51:32.850
And what that does is it
essentially brings down

00:51:32.850 --> 00:51:42.750
another factor of M. And
the Z is not touched.

00:51:42.750 --> 00:51:46.650
Or I leave the
numerator as is and take

00:51:46.650 --> 00:51:49.105
a derivative of the denominator.

00:51:49.105 --> 00:51:53.090
And the derivative of
z I've already taken.

00:51:53.090 --> 00:51:55.635
So essentially, because
it's in the denominator,

00:51:55.635 --> 00:51:58.110
I will get the minus 1.

00:51:58.110 --> 00:52:01.810
The derivative of 1 over z
will become 1 over z squared.

00:52:01.810 --> 00:52:04.020
It will also give
me that fact factor

00:52:04.020 --> 00:52:07.350
that multiplies
that factor itself.

00:52:07.350 --> 00:52:13.120
So I have e to the minus
beta H plus beta HM.

00:52:13.120 --> 00:52:17.870
And this whole
thing got squared.

00:52:17.870 --> 00:52:19.800
